Section 6: Market Distortions, Algorithmic Pricing, and Tenant Screening
When deploying mathematical formulas to hunt for "deals" in the housing market, evaluators must be acutely aware of systemic market distortions caused by enterprise-grade technology. The modern rental landscape is no longer a perfect free market of independent actors. Currently, large property management firms rely heavily on centralized algorithmic software to dictate pricing strategies.
A dominant player in this space, RealPage, controls up to 80% of the commercial revenue management market and has faced intense scrutiny and lawsuits from the U.S. Department of Justice over allegations of facilitating 21st-century price-fixing schemes. These centralized algorithms theoretically prevent landlords from lowering the rent on individual units, advising them to hold units vacant for months at a time rather than drop the base rent, thereby artificially restricting supply and elevating the pricing floor. Academic research examining the impact of algorithmic pricing on the U.S. multifamily housing market confirms these suspicions; buildings utilizing the software systematically increase prices during economic booms and resist lowering prices during busts, compared to non-adopters in the same exact market. Markets with greater algorithm penetration experienced demonstrably higher rents and lower overall occupancy rates in post-crisis periods, empirical patterns perfectly consistent with algorithmic price coordination.
Simultaneously, access to these artificially inflated units is heavily gatekept by opaque tenant screening algorithms. Companies like RentGrow mine vast troves of consumer databases—including credit history, possible criminal records, and prior landlord-tenant conflicts—to perform automated background checks. These tenant screening reports frequently serve as undocumented "shadow credit scores," assigning applicants arbitrary ratings or binary yes-or-no recommendations without transparent justification. The unreliability and lack of regulatory oversight in these screening algorithms further distort the market, restricting access for vulnerable populations and adding friction to the leasing process.
## Section 7: The Hedonic Pricing Model and Deal Score Optimization
The culmination of the True Cost mathematical framework relies entirely on the successful deployment of the Hedonic Pricing Model (HPM). First formalized by economist Sherwin Rosen in 1974, hedonic theory operates on the fundamental premise that a highly differentiated product (such as a residential apartment) can be viewed as a complex "bundle of goods," where the overall transaction value is determined strictly by the sum of its constituent, underlying characteristics.
By employing multiple regression analysis, quantitative analysts can accurately define the relationship between the price of the asset (the dependent variable) and its vast array of internal and external attributes (the independent variables). This methodology has been exponentially enhanced in recent decades through the integration of Geographic Information Systems (GIS), allowing models to process massive amounts of spatial data and accurately position properties in terms of their exact geographic coordinates and proximity to localized amenities.
While Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) linear regression remains the foundational baseline , modern real estate technology has rapidly pivoted toward advanced machine learning algorithms. Comparative studies analyzing hundreds of thousands of property transactions demonstrate that algorithms such as XGBoost, LightGBM, and CatBoost possess significantly higher predictive power than traditional OLS models, particularly due to their superior capability in handling statistical outliers and non-linear relationships.
