However, traditional OLS regressions are frequently plagued by omitted variable bias. An apartment might appear to be a massive deal (showing a deep negative residual), but the low price is actually justified by an unquantified negative trait, such as an exceptionally poor or inefficient floor plan layout. To refine the accuracy of the Deal Score and eliminate false positives, advanced methodologies actively integrate deep learning. For example, Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), specifically architectures like the Xception model, can be trained directly on raw image files of apartment floor plans. By programmatically processing the visual design and flow of the layout, the CNN generates a continuous "Floor Plan Sentiment" score. Including this unstructured, visual data variable in the overarching hedonic regression has been definitively shown to increase the model's adjusted-R^2 goodness-of-fit and radically reduce out-of-sample prediction error by up to 10.56%.
